The '''Amazon biome''' ({{lang-pt|Bioma Amazônia}}) contains the [[Amazon rainforest]], an area of [[tropical rainforest]], and other [[ecoregion]]s that cover most of the [[Amazon basin]] and some adjacent areas to the north and east. The [[biome]] contains blackwater and whitewater flooded forest, lowland and montane terra firme forest, bamboo and palm forest, savanna, sandy heath and alpine tundra. Some areas are threatened by deforestation for timber and to make way for pasture or soybean plantations.

==Location==

The Amazon biome has an area of {{convert|6700000|km2}}.{{sfn|About the Amazon – WWF Global}}{{efn|Another source gives the area of the Great Amazon as about {{convert|7800000|km2}}.{{sfn|Dubey|2014|p=100}} }}
The biome roughly corresponds to the Amazon basin, but excludes areas of the [[Andes]] to the west and [[cerrado]] (savannah) to the south, and includes lands to the northeast extending to the Atlantic ocean with similar vegetation to the Amazon basin.{{sfn|About the Amazon – WWF Global}}
J. J. Morrone (2006) defines the Amazonian subregion in this broader sense, divided into the [[Biogeography|biogeographical]] provinces of Guyana, Humid Guyana, Napo, Imeri, Roraima, Amapá, Várzea, Ucayali, Madeira, Tapajós-Xingu, Pará, Yungas and Pantanal.{{sfn|Abad-Franch|Monteiro|2007|p=2}}{{sfn|Morrone|2006}}
The [[World Wildlife Fund]] takes a similar scope, where the Amazon biome includes the [[Guiana Shield]] rain forests in the north and the [[Chiquitano dry forests]] of Bolivia.{{sfn|Intro: Amazon Ecoregions and Ecology – Yale}}

The biome covers parts of Brazil, Bolivia, Peru, Ecuador, Colombia, Venezuela, Guyana, Suriname and French Guiana.{{sfn|About the Amazon – WWF Global}}
In Brazil the biome covers more than {{convert|4100000|km2}} and covers all or parts of the states of [[Acre (state)|Acre]], [[Amazonas (Brazilian state)|Amazonas]], [[Roraima]], [[Rondônia]], [[Pará]], [[Amapá]], [[Maranhão]], [[Tocantins]] and [[Mato Grosso]].{{sfn|Tosta|Coutinho|2015|p=9}}
The Amazon biome covers 49.29% of Brazil.{{sfn|Tosta|Coutinho|2015|p=297}}
16% of the biome is in Peru.
As of 2015 about 23.4% of Peru's Amazon biome was protected, but of this less than half was fully protected.{{sfn|Wuerthner|Crist|Butler|2015|p=}}

==Physical environment==
===Terrain===
[[File:Cerros de Mavecure (Guainía, Colombia).JPG|thumb|[[Cerros de Mavecure]] in the [[Guiana Shield]] in Colombia]]
Much of the terrain of the Amazon biome, particularly around the rivers, is lowland plains.
The [[Guiana Shield]] is an area of highlands along the border between Brazil and Venezuela and Guyana.
The southern Amazonian highlands cross parts of Rondonia and Mato Grosso  and the southern parts of Amazonas and Para.{{sfn|Tosta|Coutinho|2015|p=10}}

The Amazon basin is crossed by ridges or "paleoarches" that connect the Guiana and [[Brazilian shield|Brazilian]] shields and divide it into geological sub-basins.
They are the Iquitos or Jutai Arch in Peru and [[Acre (state)|Acre]], the Carauari Arch across the [[Rio Negro (Amazon)|Rio Negro]] and [[Solimões River|Solimões]], the Purus Arch to the west of [[Manaus]], the Monte Alegre Arch to the west of the [[Tapajós]] and the Gurupa Arch to the west of [[Marajó]]. 
Under the Paleoarch model, paleobasins between the arches form centers for biological diversification.
Thus the Iquitos arch is considered the main reason for the different species of frogs and rodents and different forest types on either side of the ridge.{{sfn|Patterson|Costa|2012|p=269}}

===Soil===

The soil is generally very poor in nutrients, and areas that have been deforested often are unsuitable for agriculture or pasture.{{sfn|Pena}}
There are wide regional variations in soil types.
Thus 20% of the [[Rio Negro (Amazon)|Rio Negro]] basin is covered by [[podzol]]s and 55% by [[acrisol]]s and [[ferralsol]]s, with the remainder covered by alluvial and litholic soils and scattered areas of hydromorphic [[plinthosol]]s.
In the biome as a whole podzols cover just {{convert|136000|km2}}, or 2.7% of the area.{{sfn|Pereira|Monies|Lucas|Melfi|2016|p=332}}

===Climate===
In Brazil the average temperature of the biome is {{convert|22|to|26|C}} and average rainfall is {{convert|2300|mm}}, but there are wide variations from one region to another.{{sfn|Hilty|2012|p=46}}
The biome as a whole has annual rainfall from {{convert|1500|to|3000|mm}}, about half of which is carried by winds from the Atlantic, and the other half from [[evapotranspiration]] within the biome.
There are wide variations in total rainfall and distribution of rainfall throughout the year.{{sfn|About the Amazon – WWF Global}}

===Water===
[[File:De mãos dadas.jpg|thumb|White water of the [[Solimões River|Solimões]] and black water of the [[Rio Negro (Amazon)|Rio Negro]] converge to form the [[Amazon River]] ]]
The Amazon watershed covers about {{convert|5846100|km2}}.{{sfn|Pena}}
The [[Amazon River]] accounts for 15–16% of the total water discharged by rivers into the oceans of the world.{{sfn|About the Amazon – WWF Global}}
Rivers may be [[blackwater river|blackwater]], [[Whitewater river (river type)|whitewater]] or clearwater.
Thus the [[Rio Negro (Amazon)|Rio Negro]] ("Black River") has clear, jet-black water caused by decomposition of organic matter in swamps along its margins, combined with low levels of silt.
The [[Branco River|Rio Branco]] ("White River") and the Amazon itself have yellowish waters loaded with silt.{{sfn|Negro River – Encyclopædia Britannica}}
The Tahuayo River in the [[Tamshiyacu Tahuayo Regional Conservation Area]] of Peru is classed as a blackwater river, but often has similar chemistry to the whitewater rivers of the region since it is in the Amazon River floodplain, and receives water from the Amazon.{{sfn|Penn|Neise}}

The Amazon and its major tributaries such as the [[Xingu River|Xingu]], [[Tapajós]], [[Madeira River|Madeira]], [[Purus River|Purus]] and [[Rio Negro (Amazon)|Rio Negro]] form barriers to the [[geodispersal]] of plants, animals and even insects. Thus the [[white-fronted capuchin]] (''Cebus albifrons'') and [[hairy saki]] (''Pithecia hirsuta'') are found west of the Tapajós, while the [[white-nosed saki]] (''Chiropotes albinasus'')  is only found east of the river.{{sfn|Sears, Robin. Central Amazonia...}}
The [[World Wildlife Fund]] divides the biome into [[ecoregion]]s, often defined as the regions lying between major tributaries of the Amazon.

==Ecosystems==
[[File:Pico da Neblina.jpg|thumb|[[Pico da Neblina]] on the Brazil–Venezuela border. The [[Pico da Neblina National Park]] has a variety of ecosystems.]]
Most of the interior of the Amazon basin is covered by rainforest.{{sfn|Intro: Amazon Ecoregions and Ecology – Yale}}
The dense tropical Amazon rainforest is the largest tropical rainforest in the world.{{sfn|About the Amazon – WWF Global}}
It covers between {{convert|5500000|and|6200000|km2}} of the {{convert|6700000|to|6900000|km2}} Amazon biome.
The somewhat vague numbers are because the rainforest merges into similar biomes across its boundaries.{{sfn|Guinness|2016|p=41}}
The rainforest is [[Tropical and subtropical moist broadleaf forests|Tropical Broadleaf Forest]], so-called because most of the trees have broad leaves.{{sfn|Pena}}
The basin also holds flooded riparian forest or [[Várzea forest|várzea]], seasonal forest and [[savanna]]. 
Seasonal forest covers much of the southeast border, with marked dry seasons when there are frequent fires.{{sfn|Intro: Amazon Ecoregions and Ecology – Yale}}
The Amazon biome contains areas of other types of vegetation including grasslands, swamps, bamboos, and palm forests.{{sfn|About the Amazon – WWF Global}}

There are 53 major [[ecosystem]]s and more than 600 types of land and freshwater [[habitat]].
Of the ecosystems, 34 are forest areas covering 78% of the biome, 6 are Andean covering 1.5%, 5 are floodplains covering 5.83%, 5 are savanna covering 12.75% and two are tropical steppes covering 1.89%.
The Brazilian Amazon holds 30 of the 53 ecosystems, of which 19 are forests with 77.5% of the area.{{sfn|Hilty|2012|p=46}}
The borders of the biome hold [[ecotone]]s where it blends into other biomes such as the cerrado.{{sfn|Tosta|Coutinho|2015|p=9}}

Within and across the ecosystems of the biome there is huge biological diversity.
One source says there are an estimated 60,000 plant species, of which 30,000 are endemic.{{sfn|Dubey|2014|p=100}}
Another says there are 30,000 to 50,000 plant species.{{sfn|Hilty|2012|p=46}}
The Brazilian Ministry of the Environment as of January 2013 listed 2,500 species of trees and 30,000 species of plants.{{sfn|Tosta|Coutinho|2015|p=10}}
There are 1,400 species of fish, 163 amphibians, 387 reptiles and more than 500 mammals including 90 primates.
87% of the amphibians, 62% of reptiles, 20% of birds and 25% of mammals are endemic to the biome.{{sfn|Hilty|2012|p=46}}
109 species of lizards and [[Amphisbaena (genus)|amphisbaena]] reptiles are known to be present, and 138 species of snakes.
Of the 1,300 bird species 20% are endemic and 8.4% are endangered.{{sfn|Biswas|2013|p=57}}

A relatively small area may contain a variety of ecoregions.
Thus the [[Pico da Neblina National Park]] in the north of Amazonas, Brazil contains [[campinarana]], dense rainforest and contact between campinarana and rainforest.{{sfn|Parque Nacional do Pico da Neblina – Via Rural}}
The vegetation formations include terra firme forests and [[igapó]]s.{{sfn|Parque Nacional do Pico da Neblina – Via Rural}}
Submontane forests climb the first steps of the Guiana Plateau to about {{convert|1000|m}}, followed by montane forests.
Lichens and bromeliads are found up to {{convert|2000|m}}.
There is also [[alpine tundra]] in the tabular plateaus.{{sfn|Parque Nacional do Pico da Neblina – Via Rural}}

===Moist forest===
[[File:Kukenan Tepuy at Sunset.jpg|thumb|Kukenan Tepuy at sunset. The tops of the [[Tepui]]s have unique vegetation.]]
The Amazon basin contains several large areas of moist forest, collectively called the Amazon rainforest.
These are the [[Caquetá moist forests|Caquetá]], [[Japurá-Solimões-Negro moist forests|Japurá-Solimões-Negro]], [[Juruá-Purus moist forests|Juruá-Purus]], [[Madeira-Tapajós moist forests|Madeira-Tapajós]], [[Napo moist forests|Napo]], [[Purus-Madeira moist forests|Purus-Madeira]], [[Solimões-Japurá moist forests|Solimões-Japurá]], [[Southwest Amazon moist forests|Southwest Amazon]], [[Tapajós-Xingu moist forests|Tapajós-Xingu]], [[Tocantins-Pindara moist forests|Tocantins-Pindara]], [[Uatuma-Trombetas moist forests|Uatuma-Trombetas]], [[Ucayali moist forests|Ucayali]] and [[Xingu-Tocantins-Araguaia moist forests|Xingu-Tocantins-Araguaia]] moist forests.
Each has distinctive vegetation.{{sfn|Amazon Basin Ecoregions – Yale}}
In the broad definition favored by the [[World Wide Fund for Nature]] (WWF) the Amazon biome would also include the [[Tepui]]s, [[Table (landform)|table-top mountain]]s with unique vegetation, the [[Negro-Branco moist forests|Negro-Branco]], [[Guianan Highlands moist forests|Guianan Highlands]], [[Guianan piedmont and lowland moist forests|Guianan piedmont and lowland]] and [[Guianan moist forests|Guianan]] moist forests and the [[Guianan savanna]].{{sfn|WildFinder – WWF}}{{sfn|About the Amazon – WWF Global}}

In the southwest Amazon at least {{convert|161500|km2}} of forest are dominated by [[bamboo]]s.
These occur in areas where there has been recent tectonic uplift combined with fast mechanical erosion and poor drainage.
In each patch of bamboos all the plants flower every 27–28 years, produced huge numbers of seeds, before dying.{{sfn|Carvalho|Nelson|Bianchini|Plagnol|2013|p=1}}
The [[Chandless State Park]] is in the centre of the bamboo forest region of the south western Amazon biome, and has three endemic species of the [[Guadua]] genus of bamboo. 
Vegetation is classified as forest with palms, forest with bamboo, alluvial forest with bamboo and dense forest.{{sfn|PES Chandless – ISA|loc=Características}}

===Flooded forest===
[[File:NEO lake jau big.jpg|thumb|Igapó of [[Jaú National Park]] as seen from [[Landsat 7]] ]]
Before [[Ghillean Prance]]'s 1979 study, the local people and many scientists called the permanently waterlogged swamp on the lower Amazon "[[igapó]]" and all types of periodically flooded land "[[Várzea forest|várzea]]".{{sfn|Junk|Piedade|Wittmann|Schöngart|2010|p=15}}
A more recent definition, from Prance, is:{{sfn|Junk|Piedade|Wittmann|Schöngart|2010|p=16}}
{|class=wikitable
|-
!Type of flooding !! Type of water !! Name !! Alternative names
