|}
Major flooded areas include the [[Iquitos várzea|Iquitos]], [[Purus várzea|Purus]], [[Monte Alegre várzea|Monte Alegre]], [[Gurupa várzea|Gurupa]] and [[Marajó várzea|Marajó]] várzeas.
The Majaró várzea is at the mouth of the Amazon and is affected by both freshwater and tidal flows.{{sfn|Amazon Basin Ecoregions – Yale}}

===Campina and campinarana===

[[Campina (biome)|Campina]] is open forest on sandy soil where sunlight can reach the ground.
More than half the species of orchid in the Amazon lowlands are found in this type of forest.{{sfn|Miranda|2014|p=58}}
The terms campina and [[campinarana]] both describe white sand savannas that are very poor in nutrients.
They may be flooded periodically or seasonally, in which case the roots suffer from lack of aeration.{{sfn|Sioli|2012|p=597}}
The vegetation is stunted.{{sfn|Smith|2014|p=236}}
For some, ''campina'' is distinguished as being completely treeless.{{sfn|Secretaria de Planejamento|1975|p=16}}
The term "campinarana" is used for the transition between ''campina'' and the rainforest.{{sfn|Ab'Sáber|1996|p=xlvi}}

[[Campinarana]] is found in isolated areas of the [[Rio Negro (Amazon)|Rio Negro]] and [[Branco River|Rio Branco]] basins in the north of Brazil.{{sfn|Sears}}
Patches of campinarana, which may cover several thousand square kilometres, are found in the transitional region from the Guyana Shield to the Amazon basin.{{sfn|Rio Negro campinarana – Global Species}}
Campinarana is typically found on leached white sands around circular swampy depressions in lowland tropical moist forest.
The soil is low in nutrients, with highly acidic humus.{{sfn|Sears}}
Campinarana includes savannah, scrub and forests.{{sfn|Sears}}
The savannah is mainly composed of grasses and lichens, found in the wet plains beside lakes and rivers.{{sfn|Regiões Fitoecológicas – Campinarana – Ambiente Brasil}}
The scrub has bare sand, herbaceous plants, shrubs and trees less than {{convert|7|m}} high.{{sfn|Sears}}

The nutrient-poor Japurá-Solimões-Negro moist forest is similar to the Rio Negro Campinarana.{{sfn|Amazon Basin Ecoregions – Yale}}

===Restinga===
[[File:Lagoa dos Peixes - Lençois Maranhenses.jpg|thumb|Dunes and vegetation in [[Lençóis Maranhenses National Park]] ]]
The [[Northeastern Brazil restingas]] are coastal dune habitats that extend along the coast of northeastern Brazil, interspersed with lagoons, mangroves and patches of [[caatinga]] savanna.
The land behind the dunes may include dwarf palms, bromeliads, ferns, shrubs, grasses and scrub trees.
The more exposed areas mainly hold medium-tall grasses and scrub trees, while sheltered areas hold patches of cactus and low dry thicket.{{sfn|Northeastern Brazil restingas (NT0144)}}
Fauna include [[marmoset]]s and [[jaguarundi]]s, [[proboscis bat]]s, [[lesser sac-winged bat]]s, [[bulldog bat]]s, and [[Davy's naked-backed bat]]s, [[wood stork]], [[roseate spoonbill]], [[white-necked heron]], [[great egret]], [[cattle egret]], [[black-crowned night heron]], and [[Neotropic cormorant]].
The ecoregion has various endemic species.
The [[Lençóis Maranhenses National Park]] protects a large area of this habitat.{{sfn|Northeastern Brazil restingas (NT0144)}}

==Conservation==

Of the 1,149 federal and state protected areas in Brazil in 2014, 247 covering {{convert|1100000|km2}} were in the Amazon biome and accounted for 73% of the total area protected at the federal and state levels in Brazil.
Federal units covered {{convert|587,000|km2}} and state units covered {{convert|523,000|km2}}.{{sfn|Amazon Biome: protected areas: Coordinated audit|p=13}}
These included fully protected [[National park (Brazil)|national]] and [[State park (Brazil)|state]] parks (22%),  [[ecological station (Brazil)|ecological stations]] (9%), [[biological reserve (Brazil)|biological reserve]]s (4%)  and [[wildlife refuge (Brazil)|wildlife refuge]]s as well as sustainable use [[National forest (Brazil)|national]] and [[State forest (Brazil)|state]] forests (26%), [[Environmental protection area (Brazil)|environmental protection area]]s (17%), [[extractive reserve]]s (12%), [[sustainable development reserve (Brazil)|sustainable development reserves]] (10%),and [[area of relevant ecological interest (Brazil)|areas of ecological interest]].{{sfn|Amazon Biome: protected areas: Coordinated audit||p=14}}
More than {{convert|15000|km2}} of the Brazilian Amazon biome was deforested in 2008–12, of which only 6% took place within protected areas.{{sfn|Amazon Biome: protected areas: Coordinated audit||p=17}}
71% of federal and state protected areas in Brazil suffered no deforestation in this period.{{sfn|Amazon Biome: protected areas: Coordinated audit||pp=18–19}}

Although the [[ World Economic Forum]] ranks Brazil first in the world in terms of nature tourism potential, the country is 52nd in tourism competitiveness when factors such as infrastructure are considered.
Low public use, in part due to the inaccessibility of the Amazon national and federal parks, mean that they fail to support the local economies and therefore lack support from society, especially the local communities.{{sfn|Amazon Biome: protected areas: Coordinated audit||p=28}}
The national and state forests have low levels of formal sustainable logging contracts, the [[Tapajós National Forest]] in Pará being an exception.{{sfn|Amazon Biome: protected areas: Coordinated audit||p=29}}
Brazil has strong systems for monitoring land cover and deforestation, but as of 2014 64% of managers of protected areas said they had not monitored biodiversity in the previous five years, and more than half said they did not have tools to monitor social and environmental development.{{sfn|Amazon Biome: protected areas: Coordinated audit||p=33}}

==Threats==
[[File:Rio Branco and BR-364 in 2000.jpg|thumb|[[Rio Branco, Acre|Rio Branco]] and [[BR-364]] in 2000 showing "herringbone" patterns of deforestation]]
The "[[Deforestation of the Amazon rainforest|Arc of Deforestation]]" is in the eastern and southern borders of the biome.{{sfn|Barbosa|2015|p=31}}
As of 2006 about 16% of the Amazon biome in Brazil had been deforested.{{sfn|Landers|2007|p=4}}
Satellite images show that in the 2006–11 period total deforestation in the Amazon biome was {{convert|45100|km2}}, of which {{convert|34700|ha}} were in the three soy-producing states of Mato Grosso, Para and Rondonia.
A 2009 survey showed that of 620 recently deforested areas 203, or 32%, had been converted to pasture while 12, or less than 1%, were being used for soybeans.{{sfn|Barbosa|2015|p=97}}

The biome is not the same as the [[Amazônia Legal]], which covers a larger area of Brazil.{{sfn|Barbosa|2015|p=23}}
The Amazon biome covers about 82% of the Legal Amazon if cerrado and campinarana are excluded.{{sfn|Brandão|Schoneveld|2015|p=3}}
Defenders of soybean farming point out that the soybean farms in the Amazonia Legal mostly occupy cerrado areas, not the Amazon biome.{{sfn|Barbosa|2015|p=23}}
A statement by [[Cargill]] in 2006 said, "Soy occupies less than 0.6 percent of the land in the Amazon biome today, and most of that soy is grown on the fringes of the Amazon biome in the transitional area between the ''Cerrado'' and the forest.{{sfn|Barbosa|2015|p=94}}
A 2010 assessment of soybean farmers associated with the [[Amaggi Group|Grupo André Maggi]] found that 62.55% of the properties produced 78.09% of the crop in the cerrado biome, while 37.45% produced 21.91% of the crop in the Amazon biome.{{sfn|Barbosa|2015|p=69}}

In 2000 the Brazilian government banned creation of sugarcane plantations in the Amazon biome.{{sfn|Brandão|Schoneveld|2015|p=8}}
In 2010 a presidential decree made low-interest credit available to oil palm development, but only on land that had been deforested before 2008.
This may prove an environmentally sustainable economic solution.{{sfn|Brandão|Schoneveld|2015|p=11}}

