'''Peter Herlihy''', [[University of Kansas]] [[geographer]], the Associate Director and Graduate Advisor, [[Latin American Studies]], [[University of Kansas]] and field director of the [[controversial]] U.S. [[United States Department of Defense|DOD]] funded [[México Indígena]]<ref>[http://web.ku.edu/~mexind/index.htm Mexico Indigena] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080820143854/http://web.ku.edu/~mexind/index.htm |date=2008-08-20 }} web.ku.edu</ref> project known as the [[Isaiah Bowman|Bowman]] [[research|Expedition]]s, an initiative of the [[American Geographical Society]] to organize international teams of geographers to research potentially ''important'' [[Location (geography)|place]]-based issues and restore the role of [[geographers]] as advisers to [[U.S. government]] [[foreign policy]] makers. The stated [[Objective (goal)|objective]] of the [[México Indígena]] project is to produce [[map]]s of the “[[Digital data|digital]] human [[terrain]],” of the region's [[indigenous peoples]].<ref>http://openanthropology.wordpress.com/2009/01/29/contemporary-colonial-scholarship-and-the-spreading-human-terrain-system-ags-bowman-expeditions-zapotec-indians-and-onto-the-caribbean/</ref>

